# Marlin V3 Automation

This workspace is a Marlin V3 Human-in-the-Loop (HITL) task automation suite.

## Critical Rule

DO NOT take any workflow action, generate any submittable text, or make any
decision on your own. Everything you need to know is in two files:

1. **`automation/playbook.md`** -- the complete workflow, rules, procedures,
   evaluation criteria, and step-by-step instructions for every phase.
   Read this file FIRST whenever the user wants to do anything related to
   Marlin tasks (starting a task, analyzing repos/PRs, generating prompts,
   running turns, writing feedback, submitting). Every answer to "how do I
   do X" is in the playbook. Follow it exactly.

2. **`docs/HUMANIZER_PROMPT.md`** -- writing style rules that MUST be applied
   to ALL generated text (prompts, feedback, evaluations, reflections,
   follow-ups, edge cases, acceptance criteria, repo/PR definitions).
   Read this file and apply its rules to every piece of text you generate.
   No exceptions.

Do not improvise, do not guess, do not rely on your own knowledge of
Marlin or HITL processes. The playbook is the single source of truth.
If something isnt covered in the playbook, ask the user.

## Grounding Rule (Non-Negotiable)

Before writing ANY feedback text, you MUST:
1. Run `bash automation/hfi_orchestrator.sh capture-diffs <turn>` to save diffs
2. Run `bash automation/hfi_orchestrator.sh capture-traces <turn>` to save traces
3. Run `bash automation/hfi_orchestrator.sh compare-diffs <turn>` to get scope/similarity analysis
4. Read the saved diff files COMPLETELY before making any claims
5. For every claim about what a model did, find the exact diff hunk proving it
6. Before claiming X is unique to one model, search the other model's diff for X
7. Never cite test files, line numbers, or compile errors without verifying them in the diff/trace

These rules exist because grounding failures caused a task rejection.
See the "Grounding Rules" section in `automation/playbook.md`.

## Process Rule

Always use the orchestrator commands. Never bypass them with raw tmux commands.
The orchestrator saves audit logs, creates backups, and enforces step ordering.
